                         *******************
                         *   HEADER FILES  *
                         *******************

    A header file, sometimes referred to as a "rooms.h" file, makes
it easier for you to code, and easier for others to read your code.
A header file (often called "rooms.h") is a file in your directory
which consists of a list of #define statements.  These statements
define constants as a partial pathname for your code.
    For instance, a basic rooms.h file might contain:
 
#define MYROOT       "/players/myname/"
#define MYROOM       MYROOT+"rooms/"
#define MYWEAP       MYROOT+"weapons/"
#define MYARMOR      MYROOT+"armor/"
#define MYNPC        MYROOT+"npc/"
#define MYITEM       MYROOT+"objects/"

   If you had two separate areas, one in Kerei and one in Souvrael,
you might also have:

#define MYSOUV       MYROOM+"souvrael/"
#define MYKER        MYROOM+"kerei/"

    You could then use those definitions to #define others.

    IMPORTANT:  Make sure that the constants you choose aren't
used elsewhere, or it will cause an error.  For instance, ROOM
is defined as an inheritable for the basic mudlib room.  If you
try to use:

#define ROOM     "blah"

then you will get an error, because you're trying to re-define
something that is already defined elsewhere.

    Once you've created your header file, you can use it to help
you generate code for rooms and objects.  Just add the following
line to all your area files:
 
#include "../rooms.h"
 
assuming your files are one "directory level" down from your root
directory.  (If "/players/myname" is your root directory, then
"/players/myname/rooms" is one level down, "/players/myname/rooms/blah"
is two levels down, and so on.)  If the file in question is more than
one level down, simply add one extra "../" to the beginning of the
#include statement for each additional level.

    Note that this is a relative path.  Do not use an absolute path
(for example, #include "/players/myname/rooms.h") -- if your area was
ever moved, you would then have to change every file, rather than
just changing the header file.

    You can then use the definitions in your code.  For instance:
 
add_clone(MYNPC + "demon",1);
make_object("sword", MYWEAP + "sword", 1);
add_exit("north", MYROOM + "room2");
 
    "Abbreviating" filepaths in this way makes your code much
easier to read, and also easier for you to type.
